Effect of Age on performance

From the previous milestone, we remember that we saw some differences between the different classes with age. The next step is to compare them and find if the differences are significant.

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Medal, y = Age)) + geom_boxplot()

These are the medias of the age per group.

df %>% group_by(df$Medal) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Age), SD = sd(Age))
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
##   `df$Medal`  mean    SD
##   <fct>      <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Bronze      23.3  4.28
## 2 Gold        23.0  4.23
## 3 No medal    23.7  4.75
## 4 Silver      23.2  4.45

We will conduct an Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) since we have more than two means. We also need to adjust the \(\alpha\) value with the Bonferroni correction. So the new p_value is calculated as \(\alpha / K\), where \(K = \dfrac{k(k-1)}{2}\). So, the new p-value is:

# New p-value.
0.05/(4*3/2)
## [1] 0.008333333

The results of the ANOVA test are the following:

inference(y = Age, x = Medal, data = df, statistic = "mean", type = "ht", conf_level = 0.95, null = 0, alternative = "greater", method = "theoretical", order = c("Gold", "Silver", "Bronze", "No medal"))
## Warning: Ignoring null value since it's undefined for ANOVA
## Response variable: numerical
## Explanatory variable: categorical (4 levels) 
## n_Bronze = 1535, y_bar_Bronze = 23.2984, s_Bronze = 4.2837
## n_Gold = 1899, y_bar_Gold = 22.9937, s_Gold = 4.2318
## n_No medal = 19349, y_bar_No medal = 23.6983, s_No medal = 4.7545
## n_Silver = 1624, y_bar_Silver = 23.1909, s_Silver = 4.4537
## 
## ANOVA:
##              df      Sum_Sq  Mean_Sq       F  p_value
## Medal         3   1290.6426 430.2142 19.7452 < 0.0001
## Residuals 24403 531698.6479  21.7882                 
## Total     24406 532989.2905                          
## 
## Pairwise tests - t tests with pooled SD:
## # A tibble: 6 × 3
##   group1   group2    p.value
##   <chr>    <chr>       <dbl>
## 1 Gold     Bronze   5.72e- 2
## 2 No medal Bronze   1.24e- 3
## 3 No medal Gold     3.51e-10
## 4 Silver   Bronze   5.18e- 1
## 5 Silver   Gold     2.11e- 1
## 6 Silver   No medal 2.59e- 5

From these results we can notice that the p-value is less than 0.0001. Therefore, we can conclude that there is at least one pair of means where the difference is significant.

The pairs where this difference is significant (\(p\_value < 8.33\text{x}10^{-3}\)) are: * No medal vs Gold: Athletes with no medals have a higher age than top performers (athletes that earn gold medals). * No medal vs Bronze: Athletes who won bronze medals are younger than athletes with no medals. * Silver vs No medal: Interestingly, athletes that perform better than those with bronze and no medals, are older than those who perform worst.

Therefore, age might play a role in the probability of performing better in any sport.

New metric: Body Mass Index (BMI)

We can see that Height and Weight have a strong positive correlation. We decided to join both attributes into a new metric that shows the meassure of both: the BMI. This is calculated as \(BMI = \dfrac{Weight}{Height^2}\). The units are km/m\(^2\).

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) +
  geom_point(size = 0.2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  annotate("text",
    x = 160, y = 150,
    label = paste("Correlation = ", round(cor(df$Height, df$Weight, method = "pearson"), 4)))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

df <- df %>%
    mutate(BMI = Weight / (Height / 100) ** 2)

head(df, n = 10)

With these new metric, there seems to be a difference in the BMI for each performance group.

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Medal, y = BMI)) + geom_boxplot()

It seems that top athletes have a higher BMI than athletes without medals.

df %>% group_by(Medal) %>%

The results show that the p-value is less than 0.001. Meaning that there is at least one pair of means where the difference is significant. These groups are the following: * No medal vs Gold: Top athletes have a lower IBM than athletes with the lowest performance. * No medal vs Bronze: Athletes with lower performance have lower IBM than those with Bronze medals. * Silver vs No medal: Silver medal athletes have higher IBM than the athletes with the lowest performance.

res_aov <- aov(BMI ~ Medal,
  data = df
)

summary(res_aov)
##                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Medal           3    639  213.11   26.83 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   24403 193851    7.94                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
post_test <- glht(res_aov,
  linfct = mcp(Medal = "Tukey")
)
